data.content:
## What happened

In C# 14, new built-in span conversions change overload resolution. `array.Contains(num)` now resolves to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains`** (span-based) instead of **`Enumerable.Contains`**. Expression trees cannot represent span-based method calls, so this throws at runtime.

## How to fix it

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` or use `.AsEnumerable()` to force the `Enumerable.Contains` overload:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Both approaches pin the call to `System.Linq.Enumerable.Contains`, which expression trees support. This applies to any array `.Contains()` / `.Reverse()` calls inside expression trees after upgrading to .NET 10.
